<paragraph pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia procera" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia procera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its leaves with mite domatia, usually white flowers, and ribbed hypanthium. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
found this species does not overlap in flowering time with the other Jamaican endemics. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
thought 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia procera" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia procera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
highly resembled 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and placed it in a section together with the rest of Jamaican endemics. The molecular phylogeny places both Jamaican endemics sampled (including 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia procera" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia procera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) forming a well supported clade and belonging to a clade that also includes 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1850" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia rufescens" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1945" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia cuatrecasii" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cuatrecasii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia cuatrecasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia jaliscana" order="Myrtales" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaliscana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Conostegia jaliscana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the other hand falls with species of the giant stigma clade, which is centered in Central America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
